statement:
A valuation is a function $v:\{p_0,p_1,p_2,...\}\rightarrow\{T,F\}$\\
We will then extend this uniquely to a function $\tilde{v}:Form(\mathcal{L})\rightarrow\{T,F\}$ defined by:
\begin{itemize}
\item For all proposition variable $\phi$, $\tilde{v}(\phi)=v(\psi)$
\item If $\tilde{v}$ is defined for all formulas of length $\leq n$, let $\phi$ be a formula of length $n+1$, then by the Unique Readability Theorem $\phi=\lnot\psi$ or $\phi=(\psi\star\chi)$ for some $\psi,\chi$ and $\star\in\{\land,\lor,\rightarrow,\leftrightarrow\}$\\
Hence $\tilde{v}(\psi)$ and $\tilde{v}(\chi)$ are already defined so define
\center{
\begin{tabular}{c||c}
$\psi$ & $\lnot\psi$ \\ \hline \hline
$T$ & $F$ \\ \hline
$F$ & $T$
\end{tabular}
\hspace{1cm}
\begin{tabular}{c|c||c|c|c|c}
$\psi$ & $\chi$ & $(\psi\rightarrow\chi)$ & $(\psi\leftrightarrow\chi)$ & $(\psi\land\chi)$ & $(\psi\lor\chi)$ \\ \hline \hline
$T$ & $T$ & $T$ & $T$ & $T$ & $T$ \\ \hline
$T$ & $F$ & $F$ & $F$ & $F$ & $T$ \\ \hline
$F$ & $T$ & $T$ & $F$ & $F$ & $T$ \\ \hline
$F$ & $F$ & $T$ & $T$ & $F$ & $F$
\end{tabular}
}
\end{itemize}
Let $V_n$ be the set of all valuations of the first $n$ propositional variables.

proofs.text:
\begin{description}
\item[$(\Rightarrow)$] Assume $\psi\models\phi$, so for any valuation $v$, if $\tilde{v}(\psi)=T$ then $\tilde{v}(\phi)=T$.\\
Then by the truth table of $\rightarrow$, $\tilde{v}(\psi\rightarrow\phi)=T$, hence $\models(\psi\rightarrow\phi)$
\item[$(\Leftarrow)$] Assume $(\psi\rightarrow\phi)$ is a tautology let $v$ be a valuation such that $\tilde{v}(\psi)=T$, then by $tt\rightarrow$ we have $\tilde{v}(\phi)=T$. Hence $\psi\models\phi$ as $v$ was any valuation.
\end{description}

statement:
Let $\mathcal L_0=\mathcal L[\{\lnot,\rightarrow\}]$, then the system $\mathcal L_0$ consists of the following axioms and rules
\begin{itemize}
\item An axiom is of the following forms (for any $\alpha,\beta,\gamma\in Form(\mathcal L_0)$)
\begin{description}
\item[(A1)] $(\alpha\rightarrow(\beta\rightarrow\alpha))$
\item[(A2)] $((\alpha\rightarrow(\beta\rightarrow\gamma))\rightarrow((\alpha\rightarrow\beta)\rightarrow(\alpha\rightarrow\gamma)))$
\item[(A3)] $((\lnot\beta\rightarrow\lnot\alpha)\rightarrow(\alpha\rightarrow\beta))$
\end{description}
\item A rule of inference is of the following form (for any $\alpha,\beta\in Form(\mathcal L_0)$)
\begin{description}
\item[(MP Modus Ponens)] From $\alpha$ and $(\alpha\rightarrow\beta)$ infer $\beta$
\end{description}
\end{itemize}
\bigskip
For any $\Gamma\subset Form(\mathcal L_0)$ we say that $\alpha$ is deducible (or provable) from the hypothesis $\Gamma$ if there is a finite sequence $\alpha_1,...,\alpha_m\in Form(\mathcal L_0)$ such that for each $i=1,...,m$ either:
\begin{enumerate}
\item $\alpha_i$ is an axiom
\item $\alpha_i\in\Gamma$
\item $\exists j<k<i$ s.t. $\alpha_i$ follows from $\alpha_j,\alpha_k$ by MP
\end{enumerate}
and that $\alpha_m=\alpha$\\
\\
The sequence $\alpha_1,...,\alpha_m$ is then called a proof of $\alpha$ from $\Gamma$ and write $\Gamma\vdash\alpha$\\
If $\Gamma=\emptyset$ then write $\vdash\alpha$ and say that $\alpha$ is a theorem of $\mathcal L_0$

proofs.text:
Assume $\Gamma\vdash\alpha$ and let $\alpha_1,...,\alpha_m=\alpha$ be a proof of $\alpha$ in $\mathcal L_0$.\\
Let $v$ be any valuation such that $\tilde{v}(\phi)=T$ for all $\phi\in\Gamma$, we will show by induction that $\tilde{v}(\alpha_1)=...=\tilde{v}(\alpha_m)=T$ so $\tilde{v}(\alpha)=T$.
\begin{description}
\item[Base case $(i=1)$:] Either $\alpha_1$ is an axiom or $\alpha_1\in\Gamma$ so by the hypothesis $\tilde{v}(\alpha_1)=T$
\item[Inductive step:] Suppose $\tilde{v}(\alpha_j)=T$ for all $j\leq i$, either $\alpha_{i+1}$ is an axiom or $\alpha_{i+1}\in\Gamma$ in which case $\tilde{v}(\alpha_{i+1})=T$, or $\alpha_{i+1}$ is derived by MP with $\alpha_j,\ \alpha_k$, by the inductive hyptothesis as $\alpha_j=(\alpha_k\rightarrow\alpha_{i+1})$, $\tilde{v}(a_k)=\tilde{v}(a_j)=\tilde{v}((\alpha_k\rightarrow\alpha_{i+1}))=T$ $\Rightarrow\tilde{v}(a_{i+1})=T$ $\Rightarrow\tilde{v}(\alpha)=T$
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item[$(\Leftarrow)$] $\Gamma\vdash\phi\Rightarrow\left.\begin{array}{l}\Gamma\cup\{\lnot\phi\}\vdash\phi\\\Gamma\cup\{\lnot\phi\}\vdash\lnot\phi\end{array}\right\}\Rightarrow\Gamma\cup\{\lnot\phi\}$ is inconsistent
\item[$(\Rightarrow)$] $\left.\begin{array}{l}\Gamma\cup\{\lnot\phi\}\vdash\alpha\\\Gamma\cup\{\lnot\phi\}\vdash\lnot\alpha\end{array}\right\}\Rightarrow\left.\begin{array}{l}\Gamma\cup\{\lnot\phi\}\vdash_{SQ}\alpha\\\Gamma\cup\{\lnot\phi\}\vdash_{SQ}\lnot\alpha\end{array}\right\}\Rightarrow_{PC}\Gamma\vdash_{SQ}\phi\Rightarrow\Gamma\vdash\phi$
\end{description}

statement:
$\Gamma\subset Form(\mathcal L_0)$ is maximally consistent if
\begin{enumerate}
\item $\Gamma$ is consistent
\item For all $\phi$, either $\Gamma\vdash\phi$ or $\Gamma\vdash\lnot\phi$
\end{enumerate}

Suppose $\Gamma$ is maximally consistency, then for all $\psi,\chi\in Form(\mathcal L_0)$
\begin{enumerate}
\item $\Gamma\vdash\lnot\psi$ iff $\Gamma\nvdash\psi$
\item $\Gamma\vdash(\psi\rightarrow\chi)$ iff either $\Gamma\vdash\lnot\psi$ or $\Gamma\vdash\chi$
\end{enumerate}

proofs.text:
\begin{enumerate}
\item
\begin{description}
\item[$(\Rightarrow)$] By consistency
\item[$(\Leftarrow)$] By maximality
\end{description}
\item
\begin{description}
\item[$(\Rightarrow)$] Suppose $\Gamma\nvdash\lnot\psi$ and $\Gamma\nvdash\chi$, then $\Gamma\vdash\psi$ and $\Gamma\vdash\lnot\chi$, so $\Gamma\vdash(\psi\rightarrow\chi)\Rightarrow_{MP}\Gamma\vdash\chi$ which is a contradiction.
\item[$(\Leftarrow)$] $\begin{array}{llll}\Gamma\vdash\lnot\psi, & \Gamma\vdash(\lnot\psi\rightarrow(\psi\rightarrow\chi)) & \Rightarrow_{MP} & \Gamma\vdash(\psi\rightarrow\chi) \\
\Gamma\vdash\chi, & \Gamma\vdash(\chi\rightarrow(\psi\rightarrow\chi)) & \Rightarrow_{MP} & \Gamma\vdash(\psi\rightarrow\chi)\end{array}$
\end{description}
\end{enumerate}

For each $i$, $\Gamma\vdash p_i$ or $\Gamma\vdash\lnot p_i$ by maximality and not both by consistency.\\
Define $v(p_i)=\left\{\begin{array}{ll}T&\text{if }\Gamma\vdash p_i\\F&\text{if }\Gamma\vdash\lnot p_i\end{array}\right.$, then claim that $\forall\phi\in Form(\mathcal L_0),\ \tilde{v}(\phi)=T$ iff $\Gamma\vdash\phi$\\
\\
Proof by induction on length $n$ of formula
\begin{description}
\item[$(n=1)$] Then $\phi=p_i$ for some $i$, so by the definition of $v$, $\tilde{v}(p_i)=T$ iff $\Gamma\vdash p_i$
\item[$(n+1)$] Suppose the conclusion is try for all formulas of length $\leq n$, then let $\phi$ be of length $n+1$,
\begin{description}
\item[(Case 1) $\phi=\lnot\psi$:] $\begin{array}{ll}&\tilde{v}(\phi)=T\\\Leftrightarrow&\tilde{v}(\psi)=F\\\Leftrightarrow&\Gamma\nvdash\psi\\\Leftrightarrow&\Gamma\vdash\lnot\psi\\\Leftrightarrow&\Gamma\vdash\phi\end{array}$
\item[(Case 2) $\phi=(\psi\rightarrow\chi)$:] $\begin{array}{ll}&\tilde{v}(\phi)=T\\\Leftrightarrow&\tilde{v}(\psi)=F\text{ or }\tilde{v}(\chi)=T\\\Leftrightarrow&\Gamma\nvdash\psi\text{ or }\Gamma\vdash\chi\\\Leftrightarrow&\Gamma\vdash\lnot\psi\text{ or }\Gamma\vdash\chi\\\Leftrightarrow&\Gamma\vdash(\psi\rightarrow\chi)\\\Leftrightarrow&\Gamma\vdash\phi\end{array}$
\end{description}
\end{description}

