statement:
Let $A,B,C$ be sets,
\begin{enumerate}
\item If $A\preceq B$ and $B\preceq C$ then $A\preceq C$
\item If $A\subset B$ then $A\preceq B$, in particular $A\preceq A$
\end{enumerate}

proofs.text:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Let $f:A\rightarrow B$ and $g:B\rightarrow C$ be injections, define $h:A\rightarrow C$ by $h(x)=g(f(x))$. Then $h(x)=h(x')$ implies $g(f(x))=g(f(x'))$, hence $y=y'$ as $g$ is an injection and similarly $x=x'$ as $f$ is an injection. Therefore $h$ is an injection, so $A\preceq C$.
\item Define $f:A\rightarrow B$ by $f(x)=x$, then $f$ is an injection so $A\preceq B$.
\end{enumerate}

By definition of being finite, $X\sim n$ for some $n$. It then suffices to prove the theorem for $X=n$.\\
\\
Prove by induction:
\begin{itemize}
\item For $n=0$, there is only one function $\emptyset\rightarrow\emptyset$ and it is both injective and surjective.
\item Suppose true for $n$, and that $f:n^+\rightarrow n^+$ is injective, suppose $f$ is not surjective, so $\exists k\not\in Range(f)$.
\begin{itemize}
\item If $k=n$, set $g=f$
\item otherwise set $g(i)=f(i)$ for $f(i)\neq n$ and $g(i)=k$ if $f(i)=n$
\end{itemize}
Then both $g:n^+\rightarrow n$ and $g|_n:n\rightarrow n-\{g(n)\}$ are injective, contradiction the IH
\end{itemize}

\begin{description}
\item[$(\Rightarrow)$ ] Clear from definitions.
\item[$(\Leftarrow)$ ] Suppose $f:X\rightarrow\omega$ is injective, then $f$ is a bijection of $X$ with $Range(f)\subset\omega$, so $Range(f)$ is countable by theorem.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\item[$(\Rightarrow)$ ] If $X$ is countably infinite, then we have a bijection $\omega\rightarrow X$ as the inverse of the bijection $X\rightarrow\omega$ from the definition. If $X$ is finite, have a bijection $f:n\rightarrow X$ for some $n\in\omega$. Observe that $n\subset\omega$ and the map is surjective, so define $\bar f(m)=f(n)$ if $m\in n$ and $\bar f(m)=0$ otherwise, then this is a surjection $\omega\rightarrow X$.
\item[$(\Leftarrow)$ ] Suppose $f:\omega\rightarrow X$ is surjective, define $g:X\rightarrow\omega$ by $g(x)=\min\{n:f(n)=x\}$, then $g$ is injective, so $X\preceq\omega$ and hence is countable.
\end{description}

statement:
If $x,x',y,y'$ are cardinal numbers such that $x\leq x'$ and $y\leq y'$, then
\begin{enumerate}
\item $x+y\leq x'+y'$
\item $x\cdot y\leq x'\cdot y'$
\item $x^y\leq x'^{y'}$
\end{enumerate}

proofs.text:
Let $X$ be a finite set and $<$ a strict total order on $X$. Let $S\subseteq X$, $S\neq\emptyset$. We know $S$ is finite and we must show it has a least element, do this by induction on $|S|$
\begin{itemize}
\item If $|S|$ then trivially the only element of $S$ is the least element.
\item Suppose true for every $T$ with $|T|\leq n$ and $|S|=n+1$. Let $f:n+1\to S$ be a bijection. Then $T=S-\{f(n)\}$, so $|T|=n$ and has a least element $t$. Then $t\neq f(n)$, then\\
\begin{tabular}{rll}$t<f(n)$&$\Rightarrow$&$t$ is the least element of $S$\\$f(n)<t$&$\Rightarrow$&$f(n)$ is the least element of $S$\end{tabular}
\end{itemize}

statement:
Let $X,Y,Z$ be sets with strict total orders
\begin{enumerate}
\item If $f:X\to Y$ is an order-isomorphism, then so is its inverse
\item If $f:X\to Y$, $g:Y\to Z$ are order-isomorphisms, then so if $g\circ f:X\to Z$
\item If $X$ is well-ordered, then any subset $Z\subseteq X$ is well-ordered by restriction
\end{enumerate}

Let $X$ be a well-ordered set, then
