Fix $\alpha$ and use induction on $\beta$
\begin{itemize}
\item If $\beta=0$, then $Y=\emptyset$, so the assertion holds.
\item If $\beta=\delta^+$, let $\phi_Y:Y\to\delta^+$ be the (unique) order isomorphism and $y=\phi_Y^{-1}(\delta)$ the least element of $Y$. Then $Z$ with induced order has order-type $\delta$ where $Z=Y-\{y\}$. Then $X\cup Z$ has order-type $\alpha+\delta$, by induction, map $\psi$. Extend this to $\bar\psi:X\cup Y\to(\alpha+\delta)^+$, where $\bar\psi(y)=\alpha+\delta$. This is an order isomorphism.
\item If $\beta$ is a limit ordinal, the for each proper initial segment $Z$ of $Y$ we have an isomorphism $Z\to\delta_Z\in\beta$. By uniqueness there all agree on common domains, so we get an order isomorphism $X\cup Z\to\alpha+\delta_Z$. The union of all these maps is an order isomorphism $X\cup Y\to\alpha+\beta$.
\end{itemize}

